    "His efforts to compile a collection of literature about African-American culture led him to establish the Associates in Negro Folk Education, an organization that published a series of analytical works about politics, history, literature, and art.": [],
    "Locke wrote <em>The Negro in Art: Past and Present</em> in 1936 and <em>The Negro in Art</em> in 1940 for the series.": [],
    "His articles on African sculpture and European art, specifically German Expressionism, served as the foundation for the development of black modernism in America.": [],
    "Locke began research for <em>The Negro in American Culture</em>, but died of heart failure in 1954 before the project could be realized.</p>": []
